01:13.000 --> 01:17.040
 And now, dear friends, here's Tony Fidel.

01:18.120 --> 01:21.240
 When did you first fall in love with computers?

01:21.240 --> 01:23.560
 Or let's say computer engineering and design?

01:23.560 --> 01:28.560
 I first fell in love with computers and programming

01:29.560 --> 01:34.440
 was at a summer school class in fifth grade

01:34.440 --> 01:36.560
 in Gross Point Farms, Michigan.

01:38.160 --> 01:40.600
 It was a simple basic programming class,

01:40.600 --> 01:42.600
 but the basic programming class was not

01:42.600 --> 01:44.680
 like you might think it was.

01:44.680 --> 01:46.080
 It was bubble cards.

01:46.080 --> 01:50.880
 So literally it was, you know, the stack of cards

01:50.880 --> 01:53.080
 and you would use a number two pencil

01:53.080 --> 01:55.920
 and you would put in your program line by line

01:55.920 --> 01:57.920
 and you'd have to make sure it was perfectly stacked

01:57.920 --> 01:59.320
 and no errors and what have you.

01:59.320 --> 02:00.920
 And you would take that set of cards

02:00.920 --> 02:04.600
 and you'd put it on this reader and it would go off

02:04.600 --> 02:09.600
 to an IBM microcomputer somewhere in the back vendor cloud.

02:09.760 --> 02:14.760
 And then you would sit on a Texas Instruments paper terminal

02:17.400 --> 02:20.960
 and it would just literally, I was just, I could write things

02:20.960 --> 02:23.640
 and it would, I could program this machine to do stuff.

02:23.640 --> 02:25.840
 And it was, you know, it was nowhere near six.

02:25.840 --> 02:27.520
 There was no graphics, right?

02:27.520 --> 02:31.120
 Oregon Trail was all in text, right?

02:31.120 --> 02:34.040
 The cards were so cumbersome that if you got one thing wrong

02:34.040 --> 02:37.880
 or out of order or a disaster or you dropped one card,

02:37.880 --> 02:39.520
 it would all fall apart.

02:39.520 --> 02:44.080
 So just doing that, you know, print F or what was it?

02:44.080 --> 02:45.440
 I can only remember what it was.

02:45.440 --> 02:48.600
 It was, you know, what the basic commands were.

02:48.600 --> 02:51.680
 But also when you say basic, you mean basic programming language.

02:51.680 --> 02:52.520
 Okay.

02:52.520 --> 02:53.360
 Basic programming.

02:53.360 --> 02:57.520
 You're writing basic programming language on paper.

02:57.520 --> 02:58.560
 On paper.

02:58.560 --> 03:00.080
 And you're calling it programming though.

03:00.080 --> 03:01.200
 It's called programming.

03:01.200 --> 03:03.640
 Yeah, you're programming this computer in, you know,

03:03.640 --> 03:06.240
 in a remote location and it came back.

03:06.240 --> 03:08.720
 So it was truly cloud computing in a way.

03:08.720 --> 03:11.320
 It was really terminal based computer.

03:11.320 --> 03:14.080
 And the input and the program are separate.

03:14.080 --> 03:17.240
 So the input to the program or they could go together.

03:17.240 --> 03:20.320
 Like, or there's no input to the program.

03:20.320 --> 03:22.320
 It just runs and it gives you output.

03:22.320 --> 03:25.000
 Yeah, it goes in and it says, it says ready.

03:25.000 --> 03:27.720
 And then you can say run and then it would run.

03:27.720 --> 03:30.000
 But to program it, you didn't type it

03:30.000 --> 03:31.480
 because it was a printer terminal.

03:31.480 --> 03:32.800
 You would make the stack of cards

03:32.800 --> 03:35.760
 and that would get it into the computer's memory.

03:35.760 --> 03:36.600
 Okay.

03:36.600 --> 03:37.960
 So where was the magic?

03:37.960 --> 03:41.520
 The magic was that you could create, you had a language

03:41.520 --> 03:43.760
 and you could create what you wanted to create, right?

03:43.760 --> 03:46.080
 You could create a world or what have you

03:46.080 --> 03:47.640
 and have this interaction.

03:47.640 --> 03:49.520
 And you could compute things.

03:49.520 --> 03:50.760
 You could, you know, do numbers.

03:50.760 --> 03:54.000
 You could, I was playing Oregon Trail, right?

03:54.000 --> 03:55.080
 So you were less like...

03:55.080 --> 03:56.720
 So you can play video games.

03:56.720 --> 03:58.040
 Wow, video.

03:58.040 --> 03:59.880
 That's right.

03:59.880 --> 04:01.240
 You could play text games

04:01.240 --> 04:03.400
 and then imagine them in your brain, right?

04:04.560 --> 04:05.760
 Oregon Trail.

04:05.760 --> 04:08.120
 There's a, this meme I saw recently,

04:08.120 --> 04:11.800
 if you want to feel bad about yourself as a programmer,

04:11.800 --> 04:16.400
 realize that one person wrote railroad tycoon.

04:16.400 --> 04:17.760
 I think that's the name of the game.

04:17.760 --> 04:20.200
 It's this cool little builder game.

04:20.200 --> 04:22.160
 One person wrote it in assembly.

04:25.520 --> 04:29.320
 So from, like from scratch and for people who don't know,

04:29.320 --> 04:31.600
 it kind of looks like a SimCity type game.

04:31.600 --> 04:35.040
 It's a city builder, but obviously centered on railroads.

04:35.040 --> 04:36.920
 And there's a nice graphics of three dimension

04:36.920 --> 04:37.960
 and all that kind of stuff.

04:37.960 --> 04:40.960
 All the things, all the rich, colorful things

04:40.960 --> 04:43.800
 you would imagine for a three dimensional video game,

04:43.800 --> 04:45.320
 all written in assembly,

04:45.320 --> 04:48.800
 meaning the lowest level code next to binary,

04:48.800 --> 04:50.160
 which is fascinating.

04:50.160 --> 04:53.520
 And that's the, you had to notice the magic

04:53.520 --> 04:55.680
 at that low level at that time.

04:55.680 --> 04:57.160
 You didn't have all the graphics.

04:57.160 --> 05:02.080
 You didn't have all the like APIs and all the sample codes

05:02.080 --> 05:04.440
 and no stack overflow, no internet, none of that.

05:04.440 --> 05:06.400
 You just had, you had to know registers.

05:06.400 --> 05:08.280
 You know, had to know the op codes.

05:08.280 --> 05:10.240
 And you had to imagine the world in your brain

05:10.240 --> 05:12.200
 of the memory structures and everything of,

05:12.200 --> 05:13.320
 there's no visualization.

05:13.320 --> 05:15.440
 You visualized it all yourself, right?

05:15.440 --> 05:16.600
 And so that was magic.

05:16.600 --> 05:18.080
 But then the next part of the magic

05:18.080 --> 05:20.400
 of where I got hooked even further

05:20.400 --> 05:22.480
 was like I'm doing these little things.

05:22.480 --> 05:25.600
 And then electronic arts came out for the Apple II.

05:25.600 --> 05:28.320
 So I got an Apple II and electronic arts came out

05:28.320 --> 05:30.000
 and I was programming and doing basic

05:30.000 --> 05:31.840
 and making my own games.

05:31.840 --> 05:34.440
 But then there were two games that really blew my mind.

05:34.440 --> 05:37.200
 One was pinball construction set.

05:37.200 --> 05:40.000
 And the other one was music construction set.

05:40.000 --> 05:43.280
 And these were both places where I could create pinball games

05:43.280 --> 05:46.480
 and I could create musical scores because I love music

05:46.480 --> 05:48.520
 and I could then play them, right?

05:48.520 --> 05:51.080
 And so when you had that, you were like,

05:51.080 --> 05:53.480
 oh, there's something very different.

05:53.480 --> 05:55.120
 So I could create myself.

05:55.120 --> 05:57.720
 But then there was others that create tools

05:57.720 --> 06:00.280
 so you could create at a visual level.

06:00.280 --> 06:02.000
 And then you would read the backstories

06:02.000 --> 06:03.760
 because electronics arts back in the day,

06:03.760 --> 06:06.240
 it was one programmer who would program

06:06.240 --> 06:08.160
 those things, each of those things.

06:08.160 --> 06:09.520
 And you could read their backstories.

06:09.520 --> 06:12.560
 It was literally like a musician or someone else.

06:12.560 --> 06:14.880
 Like you could read Rick Rubin's like, here's the thing.

06:14.880 --> 06:16.160
 They tell you all of that stuff.

06:16.160 --> 06:20.160
 And there was one guy who wrote music construction set.

06:20.160 --> 06:23.360
 He wrote it all in assembly and he was 16 years old.

06:24.560 --> 06:28.240
 And I was probably 12 or 13 at the time.

06:28.240 --> 06:32.400
 And I went, oh my, if he was able to do this

06:32.400 --> 06:34.160
 and had published, right?

06:34.160 --> 06:37.040
 And this amazing tool was created.

06:37.040 --> 06:38.240
 I'm like, what could I do?

06:38.240 --> 06:41.040
 And so then it just kept building off of that.

06:41.040 --> 06:42.880
 But really it was those seminal things,

06:42.880 --> 06:46.760
 first the introduction and then the power through programming

06:46.760 --> 06:50.160
 and turning these things into what you wanted to turn it into.

06:50.160 --> 06:53.360
 And you didn't have to be 40, 50 years old

06:53.360 --> 06:54.880
 and have PhDs.

06:54.880 --> 06:58.080
 And then I was like, okay, this is really cool.

06:58.080 --> 07:00.400
 I wish we did that with programmers

07:00.400 --> 07:01.920
 where we treated them like artists.

07:01.920 --> 07:04.720
 We would know the backstory these days today.

07:04.720 --> 07:07.040
 Not just programmers, engineers.

07:07.040 --> 07:08.480
 Engineers, designers.

07:08.480 --> 07:10.800
 Yeah, like all the things about a product

07:10.800 --> 07:13.840
 that I think we love are the little details.

07:13.840 --> 07:15.520
 And there's probably a human being

07:15.520 --> 07:18.320
 behind each of those details

07:18.320 --> 07:21.920
 that had their little inkling of genius that they put in.

07:21.920 --> 07:23.440
 And I wish we knew those stories.

07:23.440 --> 07:25.120
 That's always sad to me when I,

07:25.120 --> 07:27.520
 because obviously I love engineering

07:27.520 --> 07:29.040
 and I interact with companies

07:29.040 --> 07:31.440
 and they, you know, autonomous vehicles.

07:31.440 --> 07:32.720
 Something I'm really interested about.

07:32.720 --> 07:35.280
 And I see that companies generally,

07:35.280 --> 07:36.560
 and we'll probably talk about this,

07:36.560 --> 07:38.960
 but they seem to want to hide their engineers.

07:38.960 --> 07:42.160
 Like engineers hold the secrets.

07:42.160 --> 07:46.560
 Like the great secret, we do not speak of the great secret.

07:46.560 --> 07:50.480
 But then the result of that is you don't get to hear

07:50.480 --> 07:55.680
 their stories, the passion that is there behind the engineers.

07:55.680 --> 07:58.560
 And also the genius, the little,

07:58.560 --> 08:00.960
 there's a difference between the stuff that's patented

08:00.960 --> 08:03.680
 like the kernel of the idea

08:03.680 --> 08:06.480
 and the beautiful sort of side effects of the idea.

08:06.480 --> 08:09.120
 And I wish companies revealed the beautiful side effects

08:09.120 --> 08:10.720
 a little bit more.

08:10.720 --> 08:13.280
 But sorry for the distraction.

08:13.280 --> 08:15.680
 So what, you mentioned Apple II.

08:15.680 --> 08:18.560
 What was the first computer you fell in love with?

08:18.560 --> 08:21.280
 Like the product, the thing before you

08:21.280 --> 08:23.440
 that was a personal computer?

08:23.440 --> 08:25.040
 It was the Apple II.

08:25.040 --> 08:28.800
 So the Apple II was something I was just lusting over.

08:28.800 --> 08:31.280
 You know, it was, I think it was at the time

08:31.280 --> 08:33.840
 it was the person of the year.

08:33.840 --> 08:34.960
 Maybe it was that year.

08:34.960 --> 08:36.720
 I don't remember what, but...

08:36.720 --> 08:38.800
 Well, Apple II was the person of the year?

08:38.800 --> 08:40.480
 Yeah, for my magazine back.

08:40.480 --> 08:41.520
 And I don't remember when,

08:41.520 --> 08:42.800
 but it was around that same time.

08:42.800 --> 08:46.480
 I was so young, but I had, there was the Apple II

08:46.480 --> 08:48.880
 and I didn't know what it was, but I knew about tools

08:48.880 --> 08:50.640
 because my grandfather taught me all about tools

08:50.640 --> 08:53.040
 and creating things, right?

08:53.680 --> 08:57.920
 And I saw this thing and I had that IBM experience,

08:57.920 --> 08:59.040
 that terminal experience.

08:59.040 --> 09:01.600
 And I'm like, oh, I could have that at home, right?

09:01.600 --> 09:02.960
 And so I need to have that at home.

09:02.960 --> 09:04.800
 And the only thing that was really talked about

09:04.800 --> 09:06.800
 in our circles was the Apple II.

09:06.800 --> 09:08.080
 And I was just like, that's it.

09:08.800 --> 09:11.120
 So I jumped up and down.

09:11.120 --> 09:12.480
 It was very expensive.

09:12.480 --> 09:13.200
 I have to have this.

09:13.200 --> 09:14.320
 My parents are like, what?

09:14.320 --> 09:19.120
 You know, it was $2,500 back then in the 1981.

09:19.120 --> 09:20.880
 It was like crazy, right?

09:20.880 --> 09:22.880
 So I was like, I'm gonna make as much money

09:22.880 --> 09:23.760
 as I can this summer.

09:23.760 --> 09:25.040
 And my grandfather said,

09:25.040 --> 09:27.440
 because he helped me learn all about tools

09:27.440 --> 09:28.960
 and build things together,

09:28.960 --> 09:30.640
 I will match whatever you make

09:30.640 --> 09:32.080
 so you can get this computer.

09:32.080 --> 09:36.480
 So I worked very, very hard as a caddy, golf caddy,

09:36.480 --> 09:40.880
 cadding actually for the families at the country clubs

09:40.880 --> 09:43.280
 in the town where we lived.

09:43.840 --> 09:45.360
 And did whatever I could.

09:45.360 --> 09:48.240
 And that end of that summer got my Apple II.

09:48.240 --> 09:50.080
 And you couldn't tear it away from me.

09:50.080 --> 09:52.560
 It was my friend, it was everything.

09:52.560 --> 09:54.480
 From a product perspective,

09:54.480 --> 09:57.760
 what do you remember that was brilliant,

09:58.560 --> 10:00.960
 the design choices, the ideas behind it?

10:00.960 --> 10:02.640
 Or is it just that it exists?

10:02.640 --> 10:05.040
 Or the very idea of a personal computer

10:05.040 --> 10:06.400
 is the brilliant design choice.

10:07.040 --> 10:08.880
 Yeah, it was that I could actually have

10:08.880 --> 10:10.800
 this kind of tool in my house

10:10.800 --> 10:12.800
 and I could use it any time I wanted.

10:12.800 --> 10:14.160
 I could program it anyways.

10:14.160 --> 10:15.280
 There was no, you know,

10:15.280 --> 10:16.560
 there was no internet connection.

10:16.560 --> 10:18.640
 There was no, it was all just you.

10:18.640 --> 10:21.600
 You either loaded software that you got from someone, right?

10:22.560 --> 10:24.240
 Or you created yourself.

10:24.240 --> 10:25.680
 And then there was the whole other thing

10:25.680 --> 10:27.360
 which was started happening,

10:27.360 --> 10:28.320
 which we were doing,

10:28.320 --> 10:30.240
 and this was kind of like MP3 and stuff,

10:30.240 --> 10:32.080
 we were sharing software, right?

10:32.080 --> 10:33.920
 So you built this community of sharing software.

10:33.920 --> 10:35.600
 You would go and pirate,

10:35.600 --> 10:36.400
 that was what we called,

10:36.400 --> 10:37.680
 pirate all this software.

10:37.680 --> 10:38.560
 You never use it all,

10:38.560 --> 10:40.240
 but it was just that fun thing of like,

10:40.240 --> 10:41.680
 I'm gonna get all this other stuff

10:41.680 --> 10:44.000
 and then tear it apart and do disassembly on it

10:44.000 --> 10:45.520
 and see behind the scenes.

10:45.520 --> 10:48.480
 So you really had a sense this was your world

10:48.480 --> 10:50.160
 and you owned it, right?

10:50.160 --> 10:52.400
 And you could like literally go into every register.

10:52.400 --> 10:53.840
 We didn't have all those security layers

10:53.840 --> 10:55.040
 so like we do not like,

10:55.040 --> 10:56.480
 you could really touch bits

10:56.480 --> 10:57.440
 and you could poke bits

10:57.440 --> 10:59.120
 and you could make this light turn on.

10:59.120 --> 11:01.760
 And, you know, and the geek assignment just lit up.

11:01.760 --> 11:04.880
 Now you, there's, it's so abstract.

11:04.880 --> 11:06.320
 You know, people don't even understand.

11:06.320 --> 11:07.520
 Like usually, you know,

11:07.520 --> 11:09.040
 some programs don't even understand memory.

11:09.040 --> 11:10.640
 They just think it's unlimited, right?

11:10.640 --> 11:11.280
 Yeah.

11:11.280 --> 11:13.280
 And security, it's like,

11:13.280 --> 11:15.920
 now there's all this security that you should have,

11:15.920 --> 11:19.040
 but it's like the adults all showed up to the party

11:19.040 --> 11:21.280
 and now you can't have all the fun, right?

11:21.280 --> 11:22.640
 It's like, no, no.

11:22.640 --> 11:24.160
 You know, this was the thing where

11:24.160 --> 11:26.240
 if the power went out,

11:26.240 --> 11:27.440
 you lost your whole program.

11:27.440 --> 11:28.880
 You might've worked a whole day on it

11:28.880 --> 11:31.600
 and if you didn't press save at every other line

11:31.600 --> 11:33.200
 and you were saved, save, save,

11:33.200 --> 11:35.520
 and it would like grind, grind the disc drive

11:35.520 --> 11:36.240
 or the tape drive.

11:37.920 --> 11:41.520
 Like, every single step was contemplated

11:41.520 --> 11:44.080
 because if you didn't, you lost maybe a ton of work.

11:45.120 --> 11:47.360
 So a lot of the magic was in the software.

11:47.360 --> 11:48.800
 The fact that you could have software,

11:48.800 --> 11:51.920
 the fact that you could share software

11:51.920 --> 11:53.880
 the community around the software,

11:53.880 --> 11:55.520
 it wasn't necessarily the hardware.

11:55.520 --> 11:56.800
 Well, that was the first step,

11:56.800 --> 11:58.840
 the second step around the hardware

11:58.840 --> 12:01.240
 was I got things like the mockingboard,

12:01.240 --> 12:03.840
 which the mockingboard paired with the music construction

12:03.840 --> 12:06.360
 said you could now generate all kinds of tones and notes

12:06.360 --> 12:09.120
 and it was a synthesizer in the Apple too.

12:09.120 --> 12:11.000
 So you would plug in this card and you go,

12:11.000 --> 12:12.080
 oh my God, look at this.

12:12.080 --> 12:14.720
 And it would, you know, you could start generating

12:14.720 --> 12:17.640
 cool sounds, you know, like it was a Moog,

12:17.640 --> 12:20.320
 you know, like a Moog in a way, early Moog.

12:20.320 --> 12:21.760
 What year are we talking about?

12:21.760 --> 12:25.840
 This is 82, I think, 81, 82.

12:25.840 --> 12:28.560
 And I bet you can make all the kind of synthetic sounds

12:28.560 --> 12:30.320
 that are very cool in the 80s.

12:30.320 --> 12:32.720
 Yeah, the eight bit, you know, chip tunes, right?

12:32.720 --> 12:34.480
 Chip tunes, ding, ding, ding, ding, ding, ding.

12:34.480 --> 12:38.040
 And then, you know, when you wanted to add a joystick,

12:38.040 --> 12:40.400
 you had to pull a chip out and you had to like plug in

12:40.400 --> 12:42.320
 a dip socket to put in a joystick.

12:42.320 --> 12:45.000
 And then I was like, oh, and then I had to get more memory.

12:45.000 --> 12:45.920
 How do we do that?

12:45.920 --> 12:47.440
 And now I wanted to speed up product.

12:47.440 --> 12:51.960
 So then that turned into a company, actually, from that.

12:51.960 --> 12:54.680
 But it was in a hardware software, no one at that.

12:54.680 --> 12:57.000
 But it was all about, you know, modifying this thing

12:57.000 --> 12:57.840
 in every way.

12:57.840 --> 12:58.680
 First was software.

12:58.680 --> 13:00.200
 And then you started gaining confidence.

13:00.200 --> 13:01.920
 And then I got a little bit more money and stuff.

13:01.920 --> 13:04.320
 And then you could get into the hardware and, you know,

13:04.320 --> 13:05.160
 wire things.

13:05.160 --> 13:09.320
 And then the Apple II came with all the schematics, right?

13:09.320 --> 13:12.600
 So in the back, in the early Apple IIs,

13:12.600 --> 13:14.960
 you could open up and all the schematics were there.

13:14.960 --> 13:18.080
 You purchased the Apple II and the schematics come with it.

13:18.080 --> 13:19.600
 Yeah, it came with it.

13:19.600 --> 13:21.400
 That's an interesting choice.

13:21.400 --> 13:25.080
 That's an interesting choice from a company perspective.

13:25.080 --> 13:27.600
 Right, it was like a real maker kind of thing.

13:27.600 --> 13:28.440
 Right.

13:29.680 --> 13:32.760
 I wonder what they, so that was intentional.

13:32.760 --> 13:34.080
 Like this is. Absolutely intentional.

13:34.080 --> 13:37.320
 This is for the cutting edge folks too.

13:37.320 --> 13:38.320
 Or especially for the cutting edge.

13:38.320 --> 13:39.160
 It was only the cutting edge.

13:39.160 --> 13:41.080
 It was geeks for geeks.

13:41.080 --> 13:41.920
 Yeah.

13:41.920 --> 13:43.120
 So we were like, oh, how did they make it?

13:43.120 --> 13:45.120
 And then we got to learn through that.

13:45.120 --> 13:46.320
 Apple I did the same thing, right?

13:46.320 --> 13:48.640
 It just, Apple II became more packaged up

13:48.640 --> 13:52.000
 and had, you know, a little bit better software, right?

13:52.000 --> 13:55.280
 Came with basic and then, you know, so, so it was really,

13:55.280 --> 13:58.640
 it was, it was what we might think of as a raspberry pie today

13:58.640 --> 14:01.840
 or something like that, but not with so much software.

14:01.840 --> 14:03.920
 It was literally, and all the chips were out there.

14:03.920 --> 14:06.080
 So you could inspect the buses and the, right?

14:06.080 --> 14:08.320
 Cause everything was just broken out.

14:08.320 --> 14:13.320
 So I guess that's the idea behind stable big projects

14:13.840 --> 14:15.880
 and open source like on GitHub.

14:15.880 --> 14:18.240
 That you have the schematics there

14:18.240 --> 14:20.520
 and it's, it's kind of a product.

14:20.520 --> 14:23.640
 But I wonder why more companies don't do that kind of thing.

14:23.640 --> 14:28.640
 Like we're going to release this to a small set of people,

14:29.120 --> 14:33.880
 self selected, perhaps, that are kind of the makers,

14:33.880 --> 14:36.520
 the cutting edge folks, the builders,

14:36.520 --> 14:38.640
 the at home engineers.

14:38.640 --> 14:43.560
 Like in some way, what Tesla is doing with the beta

14:43.560 --> 14:47.480
 for the full self driving is kind of like that.

14:47.480 --> 14:49.000
 It's like selecting a group of people,

14:49.000 --> 14:51.680
 but that has to do more with you,

14:51.680 --> 14:54.360
 how safe of a driver you are versus how much

14:54.360 --> 14:56.880
 of a tinkerer you are because you don't get to tinker.

14:56.880 --> 15:00.000
 I wonder, is that a crazy idea to do

15:00.000 --> 15:02.000
 for really cutting edge technologies,

15:02.000 --> 15:05.520
 especially you're interested in like hardware stuff.

15:05.520 --> 15:06.840
 Is that crazy?

15:06.840 --> 15:10.200
 Why don't more companies do that kind of thing you think?

15:10.200 --> 15:13.560
 I think back then it was about a community

15:13.560 --> 15:15.800
 and serving that community of builders.

15:15.800 --> 15:18.160
 Now this is about people who want to take,

15:18.160 --> 15:20.760
 get the experience and want it really simple and easy.

15:20.760 --> 15:24.400
 And they're like, and so there's the audience

15:24.400 --> 15:26.160
 or they believe the audience is small

15:26.160 --> 15:27.720
 who would value those other things

15:27.720 --> 15:29.080
 that we're just talking about.

15:29.080 --> 15:30.960
 But if we look at things like Raspberry Pi

15:30.960 --> 15:33.720
 and all of these other little boards, right,

15:33.720 --> 15:36.840
 there's a whole world more than I've seen.

15:36.840 --> 15:38.960
 Like it's amazing what you can do now

15:38.960 --> 15:42.920
 with these little kits and the software that's created.

15:42.920 --> 15:45.200
 And so there's a whole nother,

15:45.200 --> 15:47.520
 I think another batch of makers and builders

15:47.520 --> 15:49.080
 that are coming up through the ranks.

15:49.080 --> 15:51.640
 And if we look at YouTube channels and stuff, right,

15:51.640 --> 15:53.240
 they take these little boards, they hack them,

15:53.240 --> 15:56.640
 then they print out the parts on their 3D printer,

15:56.640 --> 15:59.480
 assemble them and they create robots and what have you.

15:59.480 --> 16:01.880
 So I think it's happening.

16:01.880 --> 16:06.880
 It's just not as, it's just not as, I guess, raw

16:07.240 --> 16:09.960
 as it used to be, but it's there.

16:09.960 --> 16:11.840
 And it's really expanding around the world.

16:11.840 --> 16:13.280
 And that's really nice to see

16:13.280 --> 16:16.400
 because it's a whole new generation who can,

16:16.400 --> 16:17.600
 who are empowered.

16:17.600 --> 16:21.240
 I think there's a semi dormant genius amongst millions.

16:21.240 --> 16:23.560
 So like Raspberry Pi is revealing that a little bit.

16:23.560 --> 16:26.080
 It's probably, I wouldn't be surprised

16:26.080 --> 16:28.280
 if it's several million Raspberry Pi's

16:28.280 --> 16:30.000
 that have been sold.

16:30.000 --> 16:31.600
 I think more than that.

16:31.600 --> 16:36.360
 And it's kind of this quiet storm of genius,

16:36.360 --> 16:37.560
 brewing of engineers.

16:37.560 --> 16:40.000
 We don't get to hear it because they're not organized.

16:40.000 --> 16:42.280
 I mean, we get to hear it through Inklings here and there.

16:42.280 --> 16:44.720
 Like I said, YouTube, there's little communities

16:44.720 --> 16:45.680
 that are local and so on.

16:45.680 --> 16:47.160
 But if they were organized,

16:49.840 --> 16:51.760
 if a leader would emerge, no.

16:51.760 --> 16:55.000
 Okay, so when did you first start to dream

16:55.000 --> 16:58.560
 about building your own things,

16:58.560 --> 17:01.320
 designing your own products,

17:01.320 --> 17:05.120
 designing your own systems and software and hardware?

17:05.120 --> 17:09.080
 Well, in high school, there was a company

17:09.080 --> 17:12.320
 that a friend of mine founded

17:12.320 --> 17:13.560
 and I was the second employee,

17:13.560 --> 17:15.680
 it was called Quality Computers.

17:15.680 --> 17:19.240
 And it was a mail order, mail order,

17:19.240 --> 17:20.400
 cause there's no eCommerce then,

17:20.400 --> 17:21.760
 there was no internet again.

17:21.760 --> 17:23.560
 You either mailed in your little coupon

17:23.560 --> 17:25.320
 and you said, this is what I wanted to order

17:25.320 --> 17:28.800
 or you wrote in to get a catalog and delivered to you.

17:28.800 --> 17:30.800
 Turn around time and this stuff was like,

17:30.800 --> 17:32.440
 from the time you wanted, the time you bought,

17:32.440 --> 17:34.480
 it was maybe eight to 12 weeks.

17:34.480 --> 17:37.360
 And that was just the normal way of getting things.

17:37.360 --> 17:42.360
 So Quality Computers was a mail order for Apple too.

17:42.400 --> 17:46.520
 And it was software and all kinds of accessories.

17:46.520 --> 17:48.040
 So hardware accessories, so hardware,

17:48.040 --> 17:50.600
 plug in cards, joysticks, all this stuff.

17:50.600 --> 17:54.840
 And what we noticed was

17:54.840 --> 17:57.560
 there were accelerators and memory cards.

17:57.560 --> 18:00.600
 And to be able to use those cards,

18:00.600 --> 18:03.720
 you had to actually go and change the software you used

18:03.720 --> 18:05.440
 to access this new memory.

18:05.440 --> 18:07.960
 So you literally have to go and you took the program

18:07.960 --> 18:09.320
 that you had, let's say it was Appleworks,

18:09.320 --> 18:11.280
 which was like an early Microsoft office

18:11.280 --> 18:12.560
 or something like that.

18:12.560 --> 18:15.840
 And you had to literally change the code

18:15.840 --> 18:18.040
 and you would install all these patches

18:18.040 --> 18:20.360
 to then take advantage of the hardware.

18:20.360 --> 18:23.520
 So what we started creating was software on top of it

18:23.520 --> 18:27.760
 to do the automatic installation of all of these patches.

18:27.760 --> 18:30.520
 So we made it much easier to take new hardware

18:30.520 --> 18:33.360
 and then end the existing software you have

18:33.360 --> 18:35.360
 and expand it into this new world.

18:35.360 --> 18:36.520
 So it was creating tools

18:36.520 --> 18:38.280
 and that really great customer support.

18:38.280 --> 18:40.960
 And we started getting a lot of orders

18:40.960 --> 18:43.560
 because we had the software make it easier to install

18:43.560 --> 18:45.480
 to give them the superpower.

18:45.480 --> 18:47.120
 And at the same time,

18:49.000 --> 18:51.000
 they would be able to change their software

18:51.000 --> 18:53.160
 and have a new world that wasn't existing

18:53.160 --> 18:56.440
 from the companies that were creating the initial products.

18:56.440 --> 18:58.000
 And so it was more of that.

18:58.000 --> 19:00.760
 And then that happened with hard drives.

19:00.760 --> 19:04.640
 So I wrote a hard drive optimizer for the Apple II

19:04.640 --> 19:07.440
 to like read, cause you could get really fragmented.

19:07.440 --> 19:08.840
 So I wrote that piece of software

19:08.840 --> 19:10.120
 and we sold that through the company

19:10.120 --> 19:13.000
 along with the hard drives that we sold from third parties.

19:13.000 --> 19:18.000
 So that all happened in 12th grade freshman year of college.

19:20.080 --> 19:23.200
 You wrote a hard drive optimizer in 12th grade.

19:23.200 --> 19:24.040
 For the Apple II.

19:24.040 --> 19:26.760
 Yeah, between 12th and freshman year.

19:26.760 --> 19:28.440
 What programming language do you remember?

19:28.440 --> 19:29.280
 Is it assemblies?

19:29.280 --> 19:30.120
 Is it supposed to?

19:30.120 --> 19:32.080
 There were certain inner loops were assembly

19:32.080 --> 19:35.280
 and other loops actually there were really early Pascal.

19:35.280 --> 19:39.560
 No, C, C compilers.

19:39.560 --> 19:41.440
 What was the motivation behind these?

19:41.440 --> 19:43.800
 Is it to make people's lives easier?

19:43.800 --> 19:45.680
 Is it to create a thing, experience

19:45.680 --> 19:47.800
 that is simpler and simpler and simpler,

19:47.800 --> 19:50.480
 thereby more accessible to a larger number of people?

19:50.480 --> 19:52.960
 Like what, or did you just like the Tinker?

19:52.960 --> 19:54.440
 No, no, no, it was two things really.

19:54.440 --> 19:56.480
 Cause one, we wanted to sell more hardware

19:56.480 --> 19:57.640
 and software, right?

19:57.640 --> 19:59.880
 So it was like, oh, make it easier for the user.

19:59.880 --> 20:01.040
 And then the other thing was,

20:01.040 --> 20:03.720
 because I was also manning the customer support line.

20:04.720 --> 20:06.600
 People would call in and go, this doesn't work.

20:06.600 --> 20:08.160
 And I'm like, oh, I gotta go fix the hardware

20:08.160 --> 20:09.120
 and software, right?

20:09.120 --> 20:10.840
 Or I gotta fix the software to make the hardware

20:10.840 --> 20:12.400
 and the installation process better.

20:12.400 --> 20:15.960
 So my whole world was out of box experience

20:15.960 --> 20:18.480
 from when I was in high school.

20:18.480 --> 20:20.600
 Cause I had to man the customer support line,

20:20.600 --> 20:22.960
 pack the boxes and write some of the code

20:22.960 --> 20:24.680
 while we were doing, well, Joe,

20:24.680 --> 20:27.080
 Joe Gleason, who was the founder of quality computers,

20:27.080 --> 20:30.120
 he was off doing the mark, the ads,

20:30.120 --> 20:32.320
 placing the ads for the mail order,

20:32.320 --> 20:35.320
 making sure we were running the credit cards, right?

20:35.320 --> 20:36.840
 It was two of us.

20:36.840 --> 20:38.240
 And then it turned into a third,

20:38.240 --> 20:39.960
 and then we hired another person from high school

20:39.960 --> 20:41.720
 to like pack boxes so I could stay

20:41.720 --> 20:44.520
 on the customer support line or doing the software, right?

20:44.520 --> 20:47.640
 And it was all in his parents basement, right?

20:47.640 --> 20:50.240
 As you were scaling exponentially.

20:50.240 --> 20:52.640
 Scaling, right, exactly, bootstrapping.

20:52.640 --> 20:54.360
 So we'll jump around a little bit,

20:54.360 --> 20:56.480
 but what were the, you said you love music.

20:56.480 --> 20:59.720
 What were the ideas that gave birth to the iPod

20:59.720 --> 21:01.100
 if we jumped forward?

21:02.720 --> 21:05.800
 And how far back do those ideas stretch?

21:06.800 --> 21:09.600
 You know, if you look at the history of technology,

21:11.280 --> 21:14.600
 there's, I mean, not just the product,

21:14.600 --> 21:17.960
 but the idea is truly revolutionary.

21:17.960 --> 21:21.220
 Maybe it's time has come,

21:21.220 --> 21:25.760
 but just if you look at the arc of history,

21:25.760 --> 21:28.880
 instead of music, it's so fundamental

21:28.880 --> 21:30.800
 to who we are as a humanity.

21:30.800 --> 21:34.160
 To be able to put that in your pocket,

21:34.160 --> 21:36.560
 make it truly portable is fascinating.

21:36.560 --> 21:40.180
 In a way that's truly portable.

21:40.180 --> 21:44.040
 So it's digital as opposed to sort of like a Walkman

21:44.040 --> 21:45.160
 or something like that.

21:45.160 --> 21:49.760
 So what were the ideas that gave birth to the iPod?

21:49.760 --> 21:53.040
 You know, I was in love with music since I was a kid.

21:53.040 --> 21:55.760
 Just love music from, I think, second grade

21:55.760 --> 21:58.200
 when I got my first albums and stuff like that.

21:58.200 --> 21:59.680
 What kind of music were we talking about?

21:59.680 --> 22:04.000
 So this was Led Zeppelin.

22:04.000 --> 22:08.320
 This was the Stones, Hendricks, Aerosmith,

22:10.640 --> 22:14.120
 Cheap Trick, Sticks, Ted Nugent, you know,

22:14.120 --> 22:19.120
 just the real American and British rock and roll, right?

22:19.120 --> 22:20.600
 There's a bunch of people listening right now.

22:20.600 --> 22:21.920
 Who's that?

22:21.920 --> 22:22.760
 Who's that?

22:22.760 --> 22:24.120
 Led Zeppelin, what is that?

22:24.120 --> 22:24.960
 Is that for you?

22:24.960 --> 22:25.800
 Okay.

22:25.800 --> 22:26.640
 Okay.

22:27.960 --> 22:29.440
 It drove my parents crazy.

22:29.440 --> 22:30.280
 Yeah.

22:30.280 --> 22:31.680
 You just blasted it loud.

22:31.680 --> 22:32.920
 Loud, just.

22:32.920 --> 22:35.120
 And this was second, third grade, fourth grade.

22:35.120 --> 22:36.160
 I just fell in love.

22:36.160 --> 22:40.560
 And then we moved back to Detroit

22:40.560 --> 22:43.040
 and I love listening to the radio station

22:43.040 --> 22:45.000
 because there was all kinds of crazy music

22:45.000 --> 22:47.400
 because you'd have an amalgam of rock

22:47.400 --> 22:48.760
 and then funk and R&B.

22:48.760 --> 22:50.360
 And I loved to listen at night.

22:50.360 --> 22:51.720
 So I had a clock radio.

22:52.720 --> 22:55.200
 But if I had the clock radio on, everyone,

22:55.200 --> 22:58.800
 parents go, go to sleep, stop that, turn that stuff off.

22:58.800 --> 23:02.280
 So I hacked the clock radio and put a headphone jack in it.

23:02.280 --> 23:03.720
 Nice.

23:03.720 --> 23:04.560
 Right?

23:04.560 --> 23:06.320
 So I said, oh, okay.

23:07.120 --> 23:09.200
 And then I could listen to it all night

23:09.200 --> 23:10.400
 and no one could hear me, right?

23:10.400 --> 23:12.280
 And I could just sit there and, you know.

23:12.280 --> 23:13.840
 Just huddling around the radio.

23:13.840 --> 23:14.680
 Groove out.

23:14.680 --> 23:16.760
 Just listening to Zeppelin.

23:16.760 --> 23:18.560
 There we're to heaven.

23:18.560 --> 23:20.760
 What would you say is the greatest rock,

23:20.760 --> 23:23.040
 the classic rock song of all time?

23:23.040 --> 23:25.480
 Greatest classic rock song of all time.

23:25.480 --> 23:26.520
 Well, pops into mind.

23:26.520 --> 23:27.680
 Well, no, you know what?

23:27.680 --> 23:29.680
 I mean, this has to be objectively number one.

23:29.680 --> 23:30.520
 That's really hard, dude.

23:30.520 --> 23:31.360
 This is so hard.

23:31.360 --> 23:34.600
 Now you have to, this is a serious journalistic interview.

23:34.600 --> 23:35.880
 You're not going to back down

23:35.880 --> 23:36.960
 from these kinds of questions.

23:36.960 --> 23:37.880
 Oh my God.

23:37.880 --> 23:38.720
 No, I don't know.

23:38.720 --> 23:39.560
 What a challenge.

23:39.560 --> 23:40.840
 Yeah, it's hard to pick.

23:40.840 --> 23:45.640
 But to me, stairway to heaven is a safe fall.

23:45.640 --> 23:47.840
 It's like, it's so often considered

23:47.840 --> 23:49.680
 to be one of the greatest songs of all time

23:49.680 --> 23:51.720
 that you almost don't want to pick it.

23:51.720 --> 23:52.560
 Right, exactly.

23:52.560 --> 23:54.480
 But you've returned to it time and time again.

23:54.480 --> 23:58.120
 And it's like, yeah, this is something pretty special.

23:58.120 --> 24:00.760
 This is a rock opera of sorts.

24:00.760 --> 24:03.160
 Well, the rock opera that really blew me away

24:03.160 --> 24:04.760
 and still continues to blow me away

24:04.760 --> 24:07.280
 is all of Dark Side of the Moon.

24:07.280 --> 24:08.520
 Like that.

24:08.520 --> 24:10.040
 I love Zeppelin.

24:10.040 --> 24:12.160
 I can't say which one's better.

24:12.160 --> 24:13.960
 But Dark Side of the Moon for me was,

24:13.960 --> 24:16.840
 it was a, you know, audio experience, right?

24:16.840 --> 24:18.240
 The whole thing from soup to nuts,

24:18.240 --> 24:21.360
 plus all the synthesizers, all of those things.

24:21.360 --> 24:23.800
 Okay, so back to the iPod.

24:23.800 --> 24:26.560
 So that's, you from the early age, you loved music.

24:26.560 --> 24:27.600
 Loved it.

24:27.600 --> 24:28.440
 Absolutely loved it.

24:28.440 --> 24:31.160
 And, you know, always was just around it and always,

24:31.160 --> 24:33.600
 I just, it was always playing, you know,

24:34.480 --> 24:37.840
 I played it so loud that I actually heard the hearing

24:37.840 --> 24:39.680
 in my right ear.

24:39.680 --> 24:41.680
 And I still suffer from that today.

24:41.680 --> 24:43.000
 And then.

24:43.000 --> 24:43.840
 No regrets.

24:43.840 --> 24:44.920
 No regrets whatsoever.

24:44.920 --> 24:47.520
 Going to concerts and downtown Detroit

24:47.520 --> 24:48.360
 and all the crazy stuff.

24:48.360 --> 24:49.680
 So moving forward.

24:50.960 --> 24:55.000
 So in college, I was a DJ.

24:55.000 --> 24:58.680
 So I would DJ and hang out and play all the tunes I love

24:58.680 --> 25:01.080
 and whatever for the crowd.

25:01.080 --> 25:03.680
 And then I continued to do that in Silicon Valley

25:03.680 --> 25:06.800
 when I moved right after school.

25:06.800 --> 25:10.280
 And so I was belugging all of these CDs around with me.

25:10.280 --> 25:12.360
 A thousand CDs to write.

25:12.360 --> 25:16.760
 And at the same time, and so those were heavy.

25:16.760 --> 25:20.360
 And at the same time I was doing the Philips Nino and Velo.

25:20.360 --> 25:24.000
 Those were Windows CE based mobile computing products.

25:25.320 --> 25:28.040
 The Nino was the first device

25:28.040 --> 25:30.480
 to actually put Audible books on tape.

25:30.480 --> 25:33.480
 So we worked with Audible, we met in a conference

25:33.480 --> 25:35.160
 and they were like, we don't want to do hardware,

25:35.160 --> 25:36.200
 we just want to do content.

25:36.200 --> 25:37.960
 I was like, well, we have this device,

25:37.960 --> 25:39.600
 let's get it together.

25:39.600 --> 25:41.160
 And we got Audible on that.

25:41.160 --> 25:46.160
 And this was in 96 or seven, first Audible books.

25:46.240 --> 25:49.440
 And it, you know, I was like, oh my God, that's audio.

25:49.440 --> 25:51.840
 Well, what if we put music on it?

25:51.840 --> 25:52.680
 Right?

25:52.680 --> 25:56.200
 And so, and the memory was very small at the time, right?

25:56.200 --> 25:57.840
 There was almost no flash.

25:57.840 --> 25:58.680
 It was all DRAM.

25:58.680 --> 26:03.160
 When you did Audible, you stored it in DRAM, right?

26:03.160 --> 26:04.800
 Which was okay probably

26:04.800 --> 26:09.800
 because how much books do you need is the idea.

26:09.800 --> 26:12.960
 By the way, brilliant, I mean, just putting books.

26:12.960 --> 26:15.640
 I know it's probably not the sexiest of things,

26:15.640 --> 26:20.640
 but putting books on a mobile device is a brilliant step.

26:21.960 --> 26:25.400
 I don't know, sometimes can't measure

26:25.400 --> 26:29.160
 how much human progress occurred because of an invention.

26:29.160 --> 26:32.080
 Like there's the sexy, big products, but you never know.

26:32.080 --> 26:34.400
 Like Wikipedia is one of those things

26:34.400 --> 26:37.360
 that doesn't get enough, I think, credit

26:37.360 --> 26:39.720
 for the transformational effects it has.

26:39.720 --> 26:43.200
 It's not seen as the sexiest of products, but maybe it is.

26:43.200 --> 26:47.480
 When you look at human history, Wikipedia arguably

26:47.480 --> 26:51.920
 is one of the big things that basically unlocked

26:51.920 --> 26:52.760
 human knowledge.

26:52.760 --> 26:55.400
 Human knowledge and human editing and human, you know,

26:55.400 --> 26:59.480
 just the human nature of building something together.

26:59.480 --> 27:00.320
 Yeah.

27:00.320 --> 27:01.560
 So it's fascinating.

27:01.560 --> 27:02.960
 Sometimes you can't measure those things,

27:02.960 --> 27:04.920
 maybe until many, many decades later.

27:04.920 --> 27:05.920
 Anyway, sorry.

27:05.920 --> 27:09.200
 So that was the Nino, that was there.

27:09.200 --> 27:11.800
 And then there was Audible, the books.

27:11.800 --> 27:13.400
 Why not put music?

27:13.400 --> 27:16.600
 Music, and I'm carrying around the music for the DJ gigs

27:16.600 --> 27:19.400
 and you're like, wait a second, two and two together, right?

27:19.400 --> 27:20.640
 Like, let's get rid of this.

27:20.640 --> 27:23.120
 And so, and then MP3 show up.

