1:58:08.440 --> 1:58:09.440
 We see this all the time.

1:58:09.440 --> 1:58:12.640
 People like, there's not enough tablet apps today that are modified for tablet, they're

1:58:12.640 --> 1:58:14.880
 just phone apps that are grown up, right?

1:58:14.880 --> 1:58:17.440
 So then they would just be Mac touch stuff.

1:58:17.440 --> 1:58:20.440
 So you'd have to have a whole developer community.

1:58:20.440 --> 1:58:23.600
 That probably wasn't the best place to take that technology first.

1:58:23.600 --> 1:58:27.640
 So you take that technology, marry it with the full screen iPod, and the phone stuff

1:58:27.640 --> 1:58:32.560
 we were working because of the iPod phone with a rotary dial was just like a rotary phone.

1:58:32.560 --> 1:58:37.420
 We couldn't make that interface work well for data input.

1:58:37.420 --> 1:58:42.280
 You put those three together and now those were those, those three things that then created

1:58:42.280 --> 1:58:49.640
 the form or the technology and the form inside what would become the iPhone, married with

1:58:49.640 --> 1:58:55.400
 a bunch of low level software from the iPod and manufacturer software and drivers and

1:58:55.400 --> 1:59:03.840
 communication stuff, combined with a very reduced Frankenstein Mac OS.

1:59:03.840 --> 1:59:09.040
 And I mean that in the best way, it means it wasn't Mac OS just changed a little.

1:59:09.040 --> 1:59:14.040
 It was totally, things were hacked out and changed and new code was inserted and it really

1:59:14.040 --> 1:59:20.560
 was a whole set of things from all different places to make that first iPhone OS.

1:59:20.560 --> 1:59:24.360
 And then there was another team working on the apps and then another team working on

1:59:24.360 --> 1:59:27.640
 the design of how it looked overall between all that stuff.

1:59:27.640 --> 1:59:33.000
 So all of those things came together to create what we know as the first generation iPhone.

1:59:33.000 --> 1:59:39.880
 And those are all probably fascinating engineering challenges and great teams like the creating

1:59:39.880 --> 1:59:42.600
 Frankenstein OS.

1:59:42.600 --> 1:59:46.200
 That's fascinating because you're simplifying, simplifying, but then you're just pulling

1:59:46.200 --> 1:59:50.480
 different stuff from and you're basically inventing, I mean, they're probably not thinking

1:59:50.480 --> 1:59:57.240
 of it that way, but a new era of computing, a new kind of computer really is Frankenstein.

1:59:57.240 --> 1:59:58.240
 Right.

1:59:58.240 --> 1:59:59.700
 And you didn't have to run Mac software.

1:59:59.700 --> 2:00:04.520
 If you look at some of the other smartphones of the time like Windows and stuff, they were

2:00:04.520 --> 2:00:08.960
 like, we need to make sure it runs Excel and it runs Word or something like that in some

2:00:08.960 --> 2:00:09.960
 reduced thing.

2:00:09.960 --> 2:00:12.780
 This was like, no, no, no, no, this was born out of entertainment.

2:00:12.780 --> 2:00:17.160
 So we didn't have to go and take all the same application.

2:00:17.160 --> 2:00:19.280
 All those other ones was about compatibility.

2:00:19.280 --> 2:00:22.120
 This was about a whole new way of being.

2:00:22.120 --> 2:00:31.600
 What did you think about the Steve Jobs presentation of the iPhone, the sort of the first iPhone,

2:00:31.600 --> 2:00:34.960
 phone, internet communicator, and the iPod in your pocket?

2:00:34.960 --> 2:00:41.240
 Yeah, you're going to sort of present the announcing three new products kind of thing

2:00:41.240 --> 2:00:43.960
 and then saying that it's all in one.

2:00:43.960 --> 2:00:44.960
 This is a good example.

2:00:44.960 --> 2:00:52.880
 This is one of the sort of historic presentations of a product.

2:00:52.880 --> 2:00:56.800
 Clearly there's like some showmanship that works, some reason it works.

2:00:56.800 --> 2:00:57.960
 It doesn't always work.

2:00:57.960 --> 2:01:03.720
 It often doesn't work, but in this case, it often did for Steve.

2:01:03.720 --> 2:01:06.720
 How did that feel?

2:01:06.720 --> 2:01:12.320
 What part of the actually, the design process was that presentation?

2:01:12.320 --> 2:01:17.180
 You know what I mean, like from the early, because he said, so consider the why, the

2:01:17.180 --> 2:01:19.760
 press release at the very beginning.

2:01:19.760 --> 2:01:21.360
 Steve was doing that the entire time.

2:01:21.360 --> 2:01:24.720
 He was working on that story from day one.

2:01:24.720 --> 2:01:29.160
 He was pitching us this, this, this, and then this, and then he would look at our faces

2:01:29.160 --> 2:01:33.000
 because you wouldn't, most people wouldn't, at least if you're working for him, wouldn't

2:01:33.000 --> 2:01:37.160
 tell him what you really thought of what he was saying, but he would look at your faces.

2:01:37.160 --> 2:01:44.440
 And then he would talk to a few real trusted confidence outside of the organization and

2:01:44.440 --> 2:01:45.960
 see what they thought, right?

2:01:45.960 --> 2:01:49.800
 And they could give him feedback on it and they could really challenge him, but he would

2:01:49.800 --> 2:01:51.720
 also look at their faces and go, hmm.

2:01:51.720 --> 2:01:56.940
 And so when you see that, then he would modulate it and change it slightly and change it.

2:01:56.940 --> 2:02:01.560
 So he was working during all of that time on the story and the storytelling, right?

2:02:01.560 --> 2:02:05.920
 And the why's, while we're working on that and helping us refine it, just like the switch

2:02:05.920 --> 2:02:08.800
 from plastic to glass, right?

2:02:08.800 --> 2:02:10.280
 All the time working on that.

2:02:10.280 --> 2:02:15.480
 So when he comes out on stage, he does something that every marketer is told not to do.

2:02:15.480 --> 2:02:19.280
 Say, these three things are now combined in one.

2:02:19.280 --> 2:02:24.520
 That is like the, that they say that that is the laziest form of storytelling possible

2:02:24.520 --> 2:02:26.880
 for marketing, right?

2:02:26.880 --> 2:02:27.880
 Yeah.

2:02:27.880 --> 2:02:28.880
 Right?

2:02:28.880 --> 2:02:31.360
 But it was the best one because it was all those pains.

2:02:31.360 --> 2:02:36.680
 It was like, I want my iPod, but I want my communications and I want my internet browsing

2:02:36.680 --> 2:02:40.840
 because I want it on the go so I can look up things because it was in information.

2:02:40.840 --> 2:02:45.840
 And when you were on the road, you had a laptop, you had an iPod and you had a phone that,

2:02:45.840 --> 2:02:49.160
 and you had to carry all of these things with you at once.

2:02:49.160 --> 2:02:53.040
 Now we're going to solve that pain for you and put it all together.

2:02:53.040 --> 2:02:56.240
 So he was just showing you the pain and beating that virus of doubt and going, it's now in

2:02:56.240 --> 2:02:58.440
 this one magical thing.

2:02:58.440 --> 2:03:02.520
 And he could come up and masterfully tell that story because he told it almost every

2:03:02.520 --> 2:03:07.000
 day to all of these people inside very quietly.

2:03:07.000 --> 2:03:09.360
 And then it was just, right?

2:03:09.360 --> 2:03:14.720
 It was like a, you know, a Tony award winning play that had been worked on for 10 years.

2:03:14.720 --> 2:03:16.720
 But also the human came through of timing.

2:03:16.720 --> 2:03:17.720
 Of course.

2:03:17.720 --> 2:03:18.720
 It was all that.

2:03:18.720 --> 2:03:23.680
 And of course he was dramatic at certain points and he would raise his voice and a rise smile

2:03:23.680 --> 2:03:24.680
 or whatever.

2:03:24.680 --> 2:03:25.680
 Right.

2:03:25.680 --> 2:03:26.680
 It was all those touches.

2:03:26.680 --> 2:03:28.800
 It was an actor as well as a storyteller.

2:03:28.800 --> 2:03:29.800
 Yeah.

2:03:29.800 --> 2:03:32.760
 But it was the truth, right?

2:03:32.760 --> 2:03:34.080
 The truth came through.

2:03:34.080 --> 2:03:36.600
 It was a nonfiction story.

2:03:36.600 --> 2:03:41.760
 And then he added those personal flourishes on top of it for dramatic effect.

2:03:41.760 --> 2:03:45.440
 It's amazing.

2:03:45.440 --> 2:03:52.080
 So there's a designer you mentioned, Johnny Yav.

2:03:52.080 --> 2:03:55.680
 You both are brilliant designers, great human beings.

2:03:55.680 --> 2:04:01.680
 There were some battles fought in the distant past between the two of you.

2:04:01.680 --> 2:04:05.920
 Looking back, what is the positive characteristics of Johnny that made you a better person and

2:04:05.920 --> 2:04:14.200
 designer having worked with him?

2:04:14.200 --> 2:04:20.160
 Watching the process that the design team that Johnny led.

2:04:20.160 --> 2:04:22.040
 I don't know where, because that was over years.

2:04:22.040 --> 2:04:23.520
 I didn't see all of those things.

2:04:23.520 --> 2:04:29.960
 But watching the design process, because it was really a team that was about materials.

2:04:29.960 --> 2:04:31.480
 It was about form.

2:04:31.480 --> 2:04:32.760
 It was about colors.

2:04:32.760 --> 2:04:37.040
 It was about these physical characteristics.

2:04:37.040 --> 2:04:38.920
 When we talked about this earlier, it was design.

2:04:38.920 --> 2:04:39.920
 What is design?

2:04:39.920 --> 2:04:41.200
 Design is everywhere.

2:04:41.200 --> 2:04:47.760
 So what they were really focused on was form, how the feel was, how it looked, the aesthetics,

2:04:47.760 --> 2:04:50.520
 the physical aesthetics.

2:04:50.520 --> 2:04:56.480
 And watching, going through that process, I learned so much in that process.

2:04:56.480 --> 2:05:07.560
 About how to do colors, how to do materials, how to think deeply about curves and shadows,

2:05:07.560 --> 2:05:12.160
 and how it would look not just in your hand, but how it would look in the photograph you

2:05:12.160 --> 2:05:14.920
 were going to take from marketing.

2:05:14.920 --> 2:05:19.920
 So how it would look, how it would feel, all of it.

2:05:19.920 --> 2:05:28.720
 It was all of those physical things around that and watching the process to get there.

2:05:28.720 --> 2:05:31.240
 That was enlightening for me.

2:05:31.240 --> 2:05:37.280
 It opened my mind to go, oh, okay, just like there's a process for all these other things.

2:05:37.280 --> 2:05:42.640
 It wasn't just magic and you say, ha, there it is.

2:05:42.640 --> 2:05:47.360
 It was really a process of refinement, of opening the funnel at the beginning and refining

2:05:47.360 --> 2:05:53.920
 down over time to get to that final and selecting and doing the selection.

2:05:53.920 --> 2:05:59.000
 And certain types you could, certain times there were opinion based design details, but

2:05:59.000 --> 2:06:05.520
 a lot of data, a lot of data driven designs of what can we deliver in volume?

2:06:05.520 --> 2:06:06.640
 What can we do different things?

2:06:06.640 --> 2:06:09.800
 So you always had these constraints that you had to work with under.

2:06:09.800 --> 2:06:15.480
 And sometimes they and the team, not just I would say, we need this and we're like,

2:06:15.480 --> 2:06:20.000
 we can't deliver that, but maybe we were able to work together to find different design

2:06:20.000 --> 2:06:25.480
 characteristics and different implementation characteristics that could get to that point

2:06:25.480 --> 2:06:27.640
 without what they were describing.

2:06:27.640 --> 2:06:33.200
 And instead of, yes, yes, yes, no, no, no, let's find some other way to solve the problem

2:06:33.200 --> 2:06:34.200
 together.

2:06:34.200 --> 2:06:35.200
 Yeah.

2:06:35.200 --> 2:06:42.280
 And I've seen this in several companies have more closely interacted with like Tesla is

2:06:42.280 --> 2:06:50.720
 an example, sometimes, you know, talking about curves sometimes is very painful on the engineering

2:06:50.720 --> 2:06:55.680
 side to deliver a very specific kind of absolute thing.

2:06:55.680 --> 2:07:01.360
 And one question that comes up in my mind is like, well, how far should we go to try

2:07:01.360 --> 2:07:09.440
 to deliver a tiny adjustment in a curve, in the curvature or in like the whatever the

2:07:09.440 --> 2:07:15.920
 form factor is in a color or the material, when the cost is like 10x to deliver, not

2:07:15.920 --> 2:07:22.720
 financially, but just like an effort, how many, how many problems to have to solve.

2:07:22.720 --> 2:07:23.720
 I don't know.

2:07:23.720 --> 2:07:29.400
 I don't know if you can say any wisdom to that because when you're thinking about curves,

2:07:29.400 --> 2:07:35.120
 you're designing in the space of ideas, you're like platonic forms kind of thing, not always

2:07:35.120 --> 2:07:40.920
 grounded to like how much this is, how much pain is going to be involved in delivering

2:07:40.920 --> 2:07:47.280
 this, but that's as you should perhaps, because then if you're always thinking about the pain

2:07:47.280 --> 2:07:52.240
 required to deliver this thing, you'll be too conservative, you wouldn't do the wild

2:07:52.240 --> 2:07:53.240
 ideas.

2:07:53.240 --> 2:07:55.440
 Oh, right, exactly.

2:07:55.440 --> 2:07:58.600
 But you have to understand again the why behind it.

2:07:58.600 --> 2:08:04.640
 And at Nest, when we had limited resources, you know, putting a screwdriver in the box,

2:08:04.640 --> 2:08:10.000
 a custom design screwdriver in the box was born out of those experiences I had at Apple

2:08:10.000 --> 2:08:15.360
 and seeing how you can create something that's emotional, it's part of marketing and it's

2:08:15.360 --> 2:08:20.360
 part of the product experience overall, even though it seems extraneous.

2:08:20.360 --> 2:08:26.120
 I went back and made the design team and the mechanical team changed some curves on the

2:08:26.120 --> 2:08:31.360
 Nest Protect, the smoke and CO detector we did at Nest, after they had already tooled

2:08:31.360 --> 2:08:32.360
 it.

2:08:32.360 --> 2:08:35.560
 And they're saying this cost more, I said, it doesn't look right.

2:08:35.560 --> 2:08:39.400
 There is a, but they're like, oh, well, we had, I said, no, you're going to go back and

2:08:39.400 --> 2:08:40.440
 you're going to make that change.

2:08:40.440 --> 2:08:43.160
 I told you, you want, we needed to do it.

2:08:43.160 --> 2:08:45.480
 We had a better looking model that is going to get done.

2:08:45.480 --> 2:08:50.760
 I know it's going to be a terrible cost to you, but we already had this discussion and

2:08:50.760 --> 2:08:52.320
 that's the way it's going to have to be.

2:08:52.320 --> 2:08:56.840
 And I'm sorry, but it is what it is.

2:08:56.840 --> 2:09:00.200
 You know, because it's better for the customer and it looks better in the pictures and all

2:09:00.200 --> 2:09:01.200
 other stuff.

2:09:01.200 --> 2:09:02.320
 We did it and it was great.

2:09:02.320 --> 2:09:07.280
 And everyone agreed it was great at the end, but it was pain to get there.

2:09:07.280 --> 2:09:11.320
 Those are where, those little details are where the magic comes out, right?

2:09:11.320 --> 2:09:17.360
 And you know, if you don't do, if you don't take those pains and put in the love the customer

2:09:17.360 --> 2:09:21.040
 is going to feel, it's going to feel, they're either going to feel the pain or they're going

2:09:21.040 --> 2:09:23.920
 to feel the love if you put it in, right?

2:09:23.920 --> 2:09:28.320
 So it depends on, you know, how much time and effort you want to put into something

2:09:28.320 --> 2:09:30.280
 and what really matters to you.

2:09:30.280 --> 2:09:32.640
 And so how you communicate what you do.

2:09:32.640 --> 2:09:38.880
 We're human beings after all, is there something you've learned from sort of the, the tensions

2:09:38.880 --> 2:09:44.000
 that are natural or that happen in teams when they're passionate and they're trying to

2:09:44.000 --> 2:09:45.520
 solve these problems?

2:09:45.520 --> 2:09:49.880
 Is that the way of life and there's the human drama?

2:09:49.880 --> 2:09:54.400
 Is that just, is that always going, is that, it is what it is?

2:09:54.400 --> 2:09:58.800
 Is that make you better actually that the drama of the tension between personalities

2:09:58.800 --> 2:10:00.680
 and all that kind of stuff?

2:10:00.680 --> 2:10:06.560
 Look, a roller coaster ride without ups and downs is no fun.

2:10:06.560 --> 2:10:08.120
 It's the journey.

2:10:08.120 --> 2:10:12.800
 It's the journey that brings, it brings out the best in everyone.

2:10:12.800 --> 2:10:19.920
 We're forged, we're tempered by those experiences, not all the ups, but also the downs.

2:10:19.920 --> 2:10:22.280
 And that's when you get the humanity and the connection.

2:10:22.280 --> 2:10:27.400
 And we can tell these stories till we're blue in the face and smile every time because we

2:10:27.400 --> 2:10:32.320
 did something together that we, each of us couldn't do a part, but when it comes together,

2:10:32.320 --> 2:10:34.120
 that's where all the emotions happen.

2:10:34.120 --> 2:10:37.800
 And that's where, if it's born out of the right reasons and the right story and the

2:10:37.800 --> 2:10:42.240
 right way, that's where the magic happens, not just for the customer, but for how it

2:10:42.240 --> 2:10:45.520
 transforms each person who is working on it.

2:10:45.520 --> 2:10:50.240
 And they will never forget those experiences in their life, positively and negatively that

2:10:50.240 --> 2:10:54.640
 happened at the time, but they look back and it's only positive because they did something

2:10:54.640 --> 2:10:56.920
 that mattered.

2:10:56.920 --> 2:11:04.280
 Had another brilliant idea that you brought to life is Nest, Nest thermostats and the

2:11:04.280 --> 2:11:07.120
 big umbrella of Nest.

2:11:07.120 --> 2:11:16.560
 Again, as part of this Netflix series, season three, what was the most memorable, the most

2:11:16.560 --> 2:11:25.640
 painful, the most insight, lead and challenge you had to overcome to bring Nest to life?

2:11:25.640 --> 2:11:38.040
 Well, the first thing for me was making someone care about their thermostat.

2:11:38.040 --> 2:11:39.640
 No one considers it.

2:11:39.640 --> 2:11:41.720
 They never had any customer choice.

2:11:41.720 --> 2:11:43.240
 They didn't install it.

2:11:43.240 --> 2:11:47.200
 They usually don't even use it because it's so complicated or what have you.

2:11:47.200 --> 2:11:48.800
 They just, they bitch at it.

2:11:48.800 --> 2:11:54.360
 They hide it in the corner and then they just pay the bill of whatever it is.

2:11:54.360 --> 2:11:58.240
 It's totally unloved, unconsidered.

2:11:58.240 --> 2:11:59.600
 So how do you wake up?

2:11:59.600 --> 2:12:03.760
 Like I said, the virus of doubt, how do you wake that up and get people going, remember

2:12:03.760 --> 2:12:07.200
 every day when you go in and it's like, you're just frustrated and then you get the bill

2:12:07.200 --> 2:12:08.200
 and you pay the bill.

2:12:08.200 --> 2:12:09.200
 So you have to do that.

2:12:09.200 --> 2:12:10.200
 So that was one thing.

2:12:10.200 --> 2:12:14.080
 I think the other big one was not delivering, it was, all of it was hard.

2:12:14.080 --> 2:12:15.080
 It was constrained.

2:12:15.080 --> 2:12:16.360
 We had only so much stuff.

2:12:16.360 --> 2:12:17.800
 We were bootstrapped.

2:12:17.800 --> 2:12:19.120
 We didn't have massive funding.

2:12:19.120 --> 2:12:22.480
 We didn't get hundreds of millions of dollars, but we did it for the right reasons.

2:12:22.480 --> 2:12:27.920
 But I think the other big part of it was not just building a disruptive product because

2:12:27.920 --> 2:12:29.720
 a lot of the people on the team had done that.

2:12:29.720 --> 2:12:35.400
 We knew what we were doing and that was, if we got the design right, we could deliver

2:12:35.400 --> 2:12:40.680
 it with enough time.

2:12:40.680 --> 2:12:43.000
 It was getting the disruptive go to market.

2:12:43.000 --> 2:12:47.300
 In other words, how to take that product from the end of the production line and get it

2:12:47.300 --> 2:12:55.080
 into the customer's hands because there was no retail or customer choice in thermostats.

2:12:55.080 --> 2:12:57.840
 No one even, it was never considered purchase.

2:12:57.840 --> 2:13:00.320
 They never thought they had choice.

2:13:00.320 --> 2:13:05.440
 Some guy, usually in suspenders and a butt crack, told them, looked around, looked at

2:13:05.440 --> 2:13:10.200
 their house and said, this looks like somebody who's got as well to do.

2:13:10.200 --> 2:13:13.240
 This thermostat is not going to cost you $350.

2:13:13.240 --> 2:13:14.240
 Thank you very much.

2:13:14.240 --> 2:13:17.440
 And you're like, I'll take whatever you give me.

2:13:17.440 --> 2:13:21.800
 And then it goes into another house, it's worth $100, it was the same damn thing.

2:13:21.800 --> 2:13:23.400
 So there was no price transparency.

2:13:23.400 --> 2:13:24.400
 There was no choice.

2:13:24.400 --> 2:13:26.760
 You just got what you were given.

2:13:26.760 --> 2:13:30.880
 So how do you go, and this was an entrenched industry.

2:13:30.880 --> 2:13:36.080
 That's why there was no innovation in it because it was doing just fine because every house

2:13:36.080 --> 2:13:38.000
 needed them.

2:13:38.000 --> 2:13:47.720
 All the installers were programmed by the product deliverers, by bonuses and bonuses

2:13:47.720 --> 2:13:50.680
 to say, you're going to only carry our product, and if you sell this many, you're going to

2:13:50.680 --> 2:13:53.680
 get a free trip to Hawaii.

2:13:53.680 --> 2:13:58.240
 And for these guys who install, I get a free trip to Hawaii, that's dream for them.

2:13:58.240 --> 2:14:03.400
 So this whole channel was fully controlled by the product guys, and it was almost monopolistic

2:14:03.400 --> 2:14:05.160
 in a way.

2:14:05.160 --> 2:14:07.160
 So how do you go around that?

2:14:07.160 --> 2:14:13.160
 So creating a disruptive go to market channel, one was direct to consumer, right?

2:14:13.160 --> 2:14:18.120
 And all the marketing that was necessary to get that message across.

2:14:18.120 --> 2:14:21.920
 Another one was getting the installation right.

2:14:21.920 --> 2:14:24.540
 No one was self installing thermostats.

2:14:24.540 --> 2:14:30.720
 So how do we get enough people who are early adopters to be able to self install them confidently?

2:14:30.720 --> 2:14:35.080
 So they didn't still have to call the guy to come and install it because then he would

2:14:35.080 --> 2:14:36.320
 say, this is a crap product.

2:14:36.320 --> 2:14:38.480
 No, I got the most better product, right?

2:14:38.480 --> 2:14:40.840
 So you had to get rid of that friction.

2:14:40.840 --> 2:14:44.760
 And then ultimately, how do you get the people who were not just early adopters, but people

2:14:44.760 --> 2:14:47.640
 who needed to see it and touch it before they bought it?

2:14:47.640 --> 2:14:53.400
 How do you get that into retail when the large brands of the time of thermostats and Home

2:14:53.400 --> 2:14:58.560
 Depot and Lowe's had contracts that they couldn't bring in any other brands?

2:14:58.560 --> 2:15:03.420
 They were owning the channel all the way to where there was any sort of slight customer

2:15:03.420 --> 2:15:09.400
 choice and it was really contractor choice more than it was and consumer choice.

2:15:09.400 --> 2:15:13.680
 So all of that had to be innovated along with the product.

2:15:13.680 --> 2:15:17.560
 And so to me, that was a huge challenge and something I had never done.

2:15:17.560 --> 2:15:18.560
 Most of us had never done.

2:15:18.560 --> 2:15:23.960
 And we had to create, that was as much as a project as actually delivering the product

2:15:23.960 --> 2:15:26.200
 itself.

2:15:26.200 --> 2:15:31.200
 So it turned out to be a giant hit.

2:15:31.200 --> 2:15:36.760
 And it was acquired by Google for $3.2 billion.

2:15:36.760 --> 2:15:43.280
 As a founder and leader, just out of curiosity, in these cases of acquisition, is it always

2:15:43.280 --> 2:15:44.760
 a good thing?

2:15:44.760 --> 2:15:50.160
 Is there any part of you and the team that considered saying no?

2:15:50.160 --> 2:15:54.780
 We considered saying no all the way along the process, right?

2:15:54.780 --> 2:15:58.080
 We had all been in big companies before.

2:15:58.080 --> 2:16:03.240
 We knew what it was like and the politics and all the other stuff and what I came to

2:16:03.240 --> 2:16:08.840
 learn, especially from Phillips, because Phillips was a very, it was 375,000 people.

2:16:08.840 --> 2:16:12.000
 It was a big, it was massive company, right?

2:16:12.000 --> 2:16:13.600
 And tons of politics.

2:16:13.600 --> 2:16:15.280
 And I was like, do we want to go back into that work?

2:16:15.280 --> 2:16:19.560
 Because I had so many negative experiences from that.

2:16:19.560 --> 2:16:23.680
 But then going to Apple, which was not big, but it was big enough that it could have all

2:16:23.680 --> 2:16:24.760
 these dynamics.

2:16:24.760 --> 2:16:29.480
 But then when you saw a leader rise up and get rid of those dynamics or not allow many

2:16:29.480 --> 2:16:36.440
 of them to flourish, then you're like, oh, with the right leadership, this can be a beautiful

2:16:36.440 --> 2:16:38.080
 marriage, right?

2:16:38.080 --> 2:16:42.760
 And so for four months, we were working together with them, with Google, to make sure that

2:16:42.760 --> 2:16:46.240
 we had the right leadership and we were going to be in the right environment that it felt

2:16:46.240 --> 2:16:47.920
 right.

2:16:47.920 --> 2:16:48.920
 So that happened.

2:16:48.920 --> 2:16:50.120
 It absolutely happened.

2:16:50.120 --> 2:16:51.120
 We worked on all the details.

2:16:51.120 --> 2:16:53.280
 We didn't even talk about price.

2:16:53.280 --> 2:16:56.840
 We were talking about how's the brand going to work, who's the team going to work with,

2:16:56.840 --> 2:17:00.600
 how are we going to get IP, how are we going to do exchanges, how are we going to get budgets

2:17:00.600 --> 2:17:01.600
 and all that stuff done.

2:17:01.600 --> 2:17:04.480
 So we worked through all of that before we actually sealed any kind of deal because they

2:17:04.480 --> 2:17:05.880
 were already investor in the company.

2:17:05.880 --> 2:17:12.080
 So we already knew, they knew relatively where the end point was for the price.

2:17:12.080 --> 2:17:20.040
 So working through all those prerequisites, I knew that as a individual product company

2:17:20.040 --> 2:17:25.040
 that was trying to create a platform, no investors were going to invest in a platform

2:17:25.040 --> 2:17:30.240
 that could take three, four years and many, many hundreds of millions of dollars to build

2:17:30.240 --> 2:17:34.960
 without all kinds of new products at the same time and products that we were having, which

2:17:34.960 --> 2:17:37.600
 were successes, but they weren't even break even yet, right?

2:17:37.600 --> 2:17:39.480
 We were still developing them.

2:17:39.480 --> 2:17:44.000
 So how are we going to get more people to fund all of these things and this platform

2:17:44.000 --> 2:17:46.240
 that I really want to create?

2:17:46.240 --> 2:17:50.240
 Because my worry, and I had seen this many times in Silicon Valley, is these small startups

2:17:50.240 --> 2:17:54.720
 have bravado and they said, I'm going to take on the big guys, right?

2:17:54.720 --> 2:18:00.160
 With a platform, but when those platform guys show up and Apple says they're going to get

2:18:00.160 --> 2:18:05.080
 in the home, at the time, nobody cared, they were, they were curiously, yeah, it's curious.

2:18:05.080 --> 2:18:06.080
 What's next?

2:18:06.080 --> 2:18:07.080
 Yeah, yeah, yeah.

2:18:07.080 --> 2:18:08.080
 But Apple wasn't in the market.

2:18:08.080 --> 2:18:10.480
 Google wasn't in the market yet.

2:18:10.480 --> 2:18:11.480
 Amazon wasn't there.

2:18:11.480 --> 2:18:15.760
 Microsoft, Samsung, they were not, they were all just, that's curious.

2:18:15.760 --> 2:18:16.760
 Right?

2:18:16.760 --> 2:18:17.760
 Yeah.

2:18:17.760 --> 2:18:22.280
 And I had watched, if you said, I'm going to go challenge them, and I'm going to build

2:18:22.280 --> 2:18:26.160
 a platform, and then they all of a sudden one by one go, oh, well, we're building a

2:18:26.160 --> 2:18:27.160
 platform now.

2:18:27.160 --> 2:18:28.160
 We're building a platform.

2:18:28.160 --> 2:18:32.160
 They fudded you to death, fear, uncertainty, doubt, and the developers run away and you

2:18:32.160 --> 2:18:33.160
 can't make that platform.

2:18:33.160 --> 2:18:37.960
 So I'm like, before the landscape gets changed on us, because we've tracked so much attention,

2:18:37.960 --> 2:18:43.800
 they announced something, we need to change the landscape on them.

2:18:43.800 --> 2:18:48.080
 Let's go to the best place where we can build out the platform, have the right leadership

2:18:48.080 --> 2:18:52.600
 behind us, to help us grow this thing into what the vision it should be.

2:18:52.600 --> 2:18:56.920
 And that's what we believe we were doing with the Google acquisition.

2:18:56.920 --> 2:19:00.280
 Is it possible to take on the platforms?

2:19:00.280 --> 2:19:04.560
 So you said there's a lot of startups with Bravado and all that kind of stuff.

2:19:04.560 --> 2:19:05.560
 Right.

2:19:05.560 --> 2:19:10.000
 It doesn't mean, James Joyce, when he was 20, said, I'm going to be the greatest writer

2:19:10.000 --> 2:19:15.880
 of the 20th century before he wrote anything of value.

2:19:15.880 --> 2:19:17.680
 One of them might be actually right.

2:19:17.680 --> 2:19:26.520
 Yeah, in this modern world, so first of all, people should definitely get your book built

2:19:26.520 --> 2:19:36.320
 as just this giant number of advice on this exact question of how to build cool things,

2:19:36.320 --> 2:19:41.800
 how to build a startup, how to all the different stages of that team and hiring.

2:19:41.800 --> 2:19:43.200
 It's mostly human nature.

2:19:43.200 --> 2:19:44.200
 It's not technical.

2:19:44.200 --> 2:19:46.480
 It's mostly human nature behind it.

2:19:46.480 --> 2:19:51.480
 And it turns out it's, you know, turtles all the way down, that's human at the bottom.

2:19:51.480 --> 2:20:00.120
 Yes, so is it possible to build startups that take on the big guys, whatever that is, of

2:20:00.120 --> 2:20:01.280
 the modern era?

2:20:01.280 --> 2:20:05.440
 So for now, it's these platforms of Apple, Google, Twitter.

2:20:05.440 --> 2:20:08.800
 I don't even know, Meta, I guess, called now.

2:20:08.800 --> 2:20:09.800
 Sure.

2:20:09.800 --> 2:20:11.840
 Is it possible to take them on?

2:20:11.840 --> 2:20:12.840
 Absolutely.

2:20:12.840 --> 2:20:15.320
 But you don't take them on on their same turf.

2:20:15.320 --> 2:20:20.560
 You take them on on the turf they're going to want to have in the future, right?

2:20:20.560 --> 2:20:21.680
 Spotify is a platform.

2:20:21.680 --> 2:20:26.160
 It started as an application, is now a platform, right?

2:20:26.160 --> 2:20:28.760
 Think of WeChat.

2:20:28.760 --> 2:20:33.760
 Think of all the super apps out there that are now wallets and delivery services and

2:20:33.760 --> 2:20:39.440
 travel services and transportation services all within an app.

2:20:39.440 --> 2:20:43.400
 They've innovated in a different level, in a different space that the platform companies

2:20:43.400 --> 2:20:44.400
 weren't.

2:20:44.400 --> 2:20:45.400
 Right?

2:20:45.400 --> 2:20:49.520
 Or they, you know, Google was an app, it was an app company.

2:20:49.520 --> 2:20:51.280
 It was solving search.

2:20:51.280 --> 2:20:53.240
 And then it became a platform company.

2:20:53.240 --> 2:20:55.320
 Apple was solving personal computing.

2:20:55.320 --> 2:21:01.040
 And then it became, or iPhone was doing, you know, solving internet browsing, all that

2:21:01.040 --> 2:21:02.040
 stuff.

2:21:02.040 --> 2:21:04.480
 And then a platform company went to the app store was at it.

2:21:04.480 --> 2:21:07.720
 If you look it out, there's no such thing as building a platform company.

2:21:07.720 --> 2:21:15.040
 You build a great app first and then you can expand it and have the right to become a platform.

2:21:15.040 --> 2:21:19.360
 Your whole book is just a bunch of advice for young people.

2:21:19.360 --> 2:21:20.360
 But let me ask you.

2:21:20.360 --> 2:21:21.360
 And older people?

2:21:21.360 --> 2:21:25.440
 Well, everyone is young at heart and if you're not, you should be.

2:21:25.440 --> 2:21:30.160
 So in terms of picking a career, you have advice on this point.

2:21:30.160 --> 2:21:35.400
 What advice would you give to a person on how to pick a career?

2:21:35.400 --> 2:21:37.520
 What is it you want to learn?

2:21:37.520 --> 2:21:39.640
 And who is it you want to learn from?

2:21:39.640 --> 2:21:44.880
 Just like you pick a university, you're like, I want to go here for this expertise.

2:21:44.880 --> 2:21:50.000
 I've heard about these programs, especially graduate, graduate studies.

2:21:50.000 --> 2:21:52.800
 You go for a certain program with a certain set of people.

2:21:52.800 --> 2:21:58.520
 Why don't you do that when it comes to, you know, a job you just don't go or in a career.

2:21:58.520 --> 2:22:01.720
 You just don't go and say, I just want to go work at Google or I just want to work at

2:22:01.720 --> 2:22:02.720
 Apple.

2:22:02.720 --> 2:22:07.200
 You want to go to a certain team with a certain set of people and work with them on something

2:22:07.200 --> 2:22:10.160
 that you're really curious about and you want to learn about.

2:22:10.160 --> 2:22:19.560
 I just want to comment that it's such a subtle but a brilliant framing of just ask the question,

2:22:19.560 --> 2:22:29.680
 what do I want to learn and then see what career path is going to maximize that.

2:22:29.680 --> 2:22:31.200
 That's so interesting.

2:22:31.200 --> 2:22:36.160
 It's the first question I ask anyone who interviews with me when I say I'm going to bring somebody

2:22:36.160 --> 2:22:37.160
 on the team.

2:22:37.160 --> 2:22:39.600
 First question is, what do you want to learn?

2:22:39.600 --> 2:22:43.720
 I don't want the expert like we talked about earlier says, I'm the expert in this.

2:22:43.720 --> 2:22:46.200
 You're going to hire me as the expert.

2:22:46.200 --> 2:22:47.760
 We're doing something new.

2:22:47.760 --> 2:22:50.360
 We're not an expert because we're not an expert either.

2:22:50.360 --> 2:22:56.600
 What is it you want to learn?

2:22:56.600 --> 2:23:02.320
 On the topic of learning, what is the best way to learn?

2:23:02.320 --> 2:23:10.960
 What starting, you go into this new place, into this new world, into maybe V1, you said

2:23:10.960 --> 2:23:12.280
 you're building V1.

2:23:12.280 --> 2:23:20.440
 I mean, the whole world is full of V1s or V0s waiting for the V1 to come along.

2:23:20.440 --> 2:23:22.440
 Zero to one.

2:23:22.440 --> 2:23:25.640
 What's the process of that look like?

2:23:25.640 --> 2:23:28.160
 What's the process of learning?

2:23:28.160 --> 2:23:30.000
 How do you learn?

2:23:30.000 --> 2:23:34.400
 Well, let me put a framing and then we'll talk about that last piece.

2:23:34.400 --> 2:23:39.880
 I have now looking back, especially writing this book, I have a version one of myself,

2:23:39.880 --> 2:23:43.200
 a version two, a version three, a version four.

2:23:43.200 --> 2:23:47.960
 I had a lot of opinions about myself and what I wanted to do.

2:23:47.960 --> 2:23:52.520
 Sometimes those opinions for certain people, those opinions are formed and they get the

2:23:52.520 --> 2:23:57.600
 data from their parents and they go do what their parents told them to do or their surroundings.

2:23:57.600 --> 2:23:59.600
 My opinions was like, I want to go and learn this.

2:23:59.600 --> 2:24:00.600
 I'm curious about that.

2:24:00.600 --> 2:24:06.880
 I made the zero to one move and then over time, by doing, I was refining those things

2:24:06.880 --> 2:24:10.560
 and learning what I was really curious about and what I was really good about because I

2:24:10.560 --> 2:24:15.080
 was getting data and then I was like, then I had another set of opinions to create version

2:24:15.080 --> 2:24:17.640
 two of me and then I would go and do it.

2:24:17.640 --> 2:24:22.800
 So I was learning by doing, starting with the opinion, you're not going to get any facts.

2:24:22.800 --> 2:24:27.400
 Most people are like, where do I make the most money from my position?

2:24:27.400 --> 2:24:30.720
 They're trying to start with data.

2:24:30.720 --> 2:24:32.800
 Start with the why.

2:24:32.800 --> 2:24:33.960
 What's your curiosity?

2:24:33.960 --> 2:24:37.320
 What do you want to learn and then follow that?

2:24:37.320 --> 2:24:43.520
 I took the lowest job on the totem pole at General Magic because I wanted to get in there

2:24:43.520 --> 2:24:44.840
 to work with the right team.

2:24:44.840 --> 2:24:51.560
 I didn't even know what they were doing, but I thought that it felt right.

2:24:51.560 --> 2:24:55.800
 I was barely living above the poverty line working there, working 80 hours a week because

2:24:55.800 --> 2:24:59.520
 it was so amazing to learn just like a college student.

2:24:59.520 --> 2:25:01.080
 That's what I was doing.

2:25:01.080 --> 2:25:06.400
 And then I learned more from that and then changed those opinions into data and then

2:25:06.400 --> 2:25:07.920
 I found other opinions.

2:25:07.920 --> 2:25:11.840
 So it's the same thing, but it was by doing.

2:25:11.840 --> 2:25:15.120
 The way you find out what you want to do in life is by figuring out what you don't want

2:25:15.120 --> 2:25:16.120
 to do.

2:25:16.120 --> 2:25:22.040
 And the only way you find that out is by doing a bunch of stuff and refining it.

2:25:22.040 --> 2:25:23.040
 That's hilarious.

2:25:23.040 --> 2:25:24.960
 Yeah, that's brilliant.

2:25:24.960 --> 2:25:31.680
 So in terms of the career path of leaping into the startup world and launching a startup,

2:25:31.680 --> 2:25:37.920
 what does it take to successfully found a startup, to have a chance to succeed?

2:25:37.920 --> 2:25:46.880
 And maybe how do you decide to take that leap?

2:25:46.880 --> 2:25:53.840
 Is there sort of having found it, having been part of many V1s, many of some of the most

2:25:53.840 --> 2:25:59.120
 successful V1s ever, what's it take to take that leap?

2:25:59.120 --> 2:26:06.640
 Maybe leave your job, a cushy job at a company and do the startup.

2:26:06.640 --> 2:26:08.840
 What does it take?

2:26:08.840 --> 2:26:11.040
 It takes belief in yourself.

2:26:11.040 --> 2:26:12.680
 That's the first thing.

2:26:12.680 --> 2:26:18.040
 Belief that you can do it, not but hopefully with mirrors or mentors around you or coaches

2:26:18.040 --> 2:26:21.480
 around you to make sure you know you're not crazy.

2:26:21.480 --> 2:26:26.840
 It's a crazy smart idea, but you're not crazy and you're just working on something as a

2:26:26.840 --> 2:26:31.440
 lone mad man or woman.

2:26:31.440 --> 2:26:36.800
 You have a great idea and like I said, great ideas chase you.

2:26:36.800 --> 2:26:41.680
 In this world, there are so many people who have more ideas than they have time to implement.

2:26:41.680 --> 2:26:42.880
 I used to be like that.

2:26:42.880 --> 2:26:47.440
 I would like, oh my God, I have this idea, this idea, and you try to do all of them.

2:26:47.440 --> 2:26:51.640
 But the best ideas are the ones that you can really focus on and you shut out all those

2:26:51.640 --> 2:26:55.040
 other things and you bring them other ideas into the thing you're trying to do.

2:26:55.040 --> 2:27:00.040
 So I try to run away from a great idea and then it stalks me.

2:27:00.040 --> 2:27:03.560
 It hunts you down because you're like, ah, that's going to have this problem.

2:27:03.560 --> 2:27:05.480
 I'm going to put it aside.

2:27:05.480 --> 2:27:10.480
 And then all of a sudden, a few days later, oh, I think I know how to solve that problem

2:27:10.480 --> 2:27:15.600
 or I talked to somebody and you're just always kind of niggling around the edges of it.

2:27:15.600 --> 2:27:20.360
 And then at some point, it's like, it just becomes like this black hole that just sucks

2:27:20.360 --> 2:27:23.480
 you and you're like, I can't think about anything else but this.

2:27:23.480 --> 2:27:26.760
 It's almost like a relationship in the world, right?

2:27:26.760 --> 2:27:33.200
 When you have it with a, you find your partner, you know, you're like, hmm, wait, hmm, something.

2:27:33.200 --> 2:27:36.920
 And then you're trying to, and then all of a sudden it just, it comes together, right?

2:27:36.920 --> 2:27:37.920
 It's kind of like that.

2:27:37.920 --> 2:27:41.240
 Ultimately, Chief Folk, see, I'm different, I just dive right in.

2:27:41.240 --> 2:27:42.240
 I used to do that too.

2:27:42.240 --> 2:27:43.480
 I used to dive right in.

2:27:43.480 --> 2:27:44.480
 Yeah.

2:27:44.480 --> 2:27:49.880
 And then I learned that you need time to run away from it and so it chases you because

2:27:49.880 --> 2:27:52.600
 it makes you think harder about that story.

2:27:52.600 --> 2:27:54.000
 This is not dating advice.

2:27:54.000 --> 2:27:57.920
 We're talking about data.

2:27:57.920 --> 2:28:05.480
 But ultimately, so you have a chief focus on it, but you also said to believe in yourself.

2:28:05.480 --> 2:28:11.560
 It's not necessarily even the idea, it's the human that believe in the human being.

2:28:11.560 --> 2:28:16.520
 You have to believe in yourself and the idea that you have because if you don't have that

2:28:16.520 --> 2:28:24.200
 belief, then you can't project that to other people to say, join the team.

2:28:24.200 --> 2:28:29.680
 Let me ask you on, because you mentioned mentors and you've talked about having had incredible

2:28:29.680 --> 2:28:30.960
 mentors in your life.

2:28:30.960 --> 2:28:34.760
 You're also a mentor to a very large number of people.

2:28:34.760 --> 2:28:36.600
 What does it take to find a mentor?

2:28:36.600 --> 2:28:40.440
 How do you, how do you find a great mentor?

2:28:40.440 --> 2:28:42.960
 Actually they also find you.

2:28:42.960 --> 2:28:44.960
 Is it like with the ideas?

2:28:44.960 --> 2:28:51.560
 No, no, no, what happens is you're in the right, you have a community around you.

2:28:51.560 --> 2:28:55.720
 Because you've been building a network, because you can't do it alone, so you have to create

2:28:55.720 --> 2:29:00.880
 this network around you of relationships that don't, not transactions, but relationships

2:29:00.880 --> 2:29:05.000
 over time that you really cherish and people you talk to.

2:29:05.000 --> 2:29:11.720
 When you share vulnerable or nascent ideas with, or crazy opinions with, and then you

2:29:11.720 --> 2:29:18.520
 argue them through, but you start to see resonate, and it's not about age.

2:29:18.520 --> 2:29:20.600
 It's just about this connection.

2:29:20.600 --> 2:29:25.400
 I have mentors, obviously when I was young, all my mentors were older, and as I get older,

2:29:25.400 --> 2:29:28.680
 I have mentors who are younger than me or the same age.

2:29:28.680 --> 2:29:31.320
 They're not all just older.

2:29:31.320 --> 2:29:35.160
 It's about that connection, it's about being on that same wavelength.

2:29:35.160 --> 2:29:39.240
 But they also, they can counterbalance you.

2:29:39.240 --> 2:29:41.400
 They compliment you in some way.

2:29:41.400 --> 2:29:43.840
 My best mentors had nothing to do with technology.

2:29:43.840 --> 2:29:47.880
 They didn't know anything about technology, right, the way we know it.

2:29:47.880 --> 2:29:51.480
 They were all about human nature, and they could reflect that and help me get more human

2:29:51.480 --> 2:29:56.880
 focused and more empathetic, because I was so detailed in the technology, I needed to

2:29:56.880 --> 2:29:58.920
 see from other perspectives.

2:29:58.920 --> 2:30:02.240
 But then they wanted to learn more about the technology, right, or they thought that this

2:30:02.240 --> 2:30:04.880
 idea was so great that it should exist.

2:30:04.880 --> 2:30:06.840
 Now let's work together on that.

2:30:06.840 --> 2:30:11.800
 So it's really, they have to find you and you have to find them, and that's by sharing.

